article.headline: Montana 31, McNeese State 6
article.story: MISSOULA, Mont. (AP) -- Montana had 514 yards in total offense and didn't allow McNeese State past midfield in the second half in a 31-6 first-round playoff victory Saturday. "It was a pretty dominating effort in all three facets," said Montana coach Bobby Hauck. "It's probably as complete a game as we've played. We've had some pretty good outings, but this was, if not the best, certainly one of them." Josh Swogger passed for 259 yards and four touchdowns and Thomas Brooks-Fletcher had 13 carries for 113 yards for the Grizzlies. "We came into this game thinking, hey, we're going to run this ball, we're going to establish the run, and everything else is going to open up for you," Swogger said. "Everybody did the right thing." No. 2 Montana (11-1), which won its 11th consecutive game, is at home next Saturday against No. 10 Southern Illinois (9-3), a 36-30 winner over Tennessee-Martin. Blake Bercegeay kicked first-half field goals of 42 and 38 yards for No. 22 McNeese State (7-5). Swogger's touchdown passes were a 50-yarder to Dan Beaudin, a 14-yarder to Eric Allen and third-quarter scoring passes of 8 and 11 yards to Craig Chambers. McNeese State went up 3-0 on Bercegeay's 42-yard field goal with 10:11 left in the first quarter, before Montana answered with the 50-yard TD pass from Swogger to Beaudin. A 38-yard field goal by Bercegeay with 10:24 left in the half pulled McNeese State within 7-6, but the Cowboys couldn't score again. "They lined up and kind of ran it right at us," said McNeese coach Matt Viator. "Their physical size I thought really affected the game. You've just got to give them credit. They did a really good job and they were certainly the better team today." Dan Carpenter kicked a 22-yard field goal with 3:09 left in the half to give the Grizzlies a 10-6 lead. Montana got the ball back with just over a minute to play, after Kroy Biermann sacked backup quarterback Mark Fontenot on a third-and-6 play late in the second quarter. McNeese threw an incomplete pass on second-and-1 and then was called for a false start on third down. "It's probably a call in the game that I wish I'd have had back," Viator said. "It's second-and-1, and certainly we didn't want to give Montana the ball back. So my thinking was we take the shot on second-and-1 and if we didn't get it, come back and get the first down on third down. Well, we jumped offsides and Montana ended up getting the ball back, so I think that was a crucial time of the game." Montana ran its two-minute drill in the final 1:16, covering 67 yards in seven plays, including the 14-yard TD pass from Swogger to Allen. Montana led 17-6 with 13 seconds left in the half. "That was a pretty textbook clock drive," Hauck said. "For sure, it was a good deal for us to go in with that touchdown going into the locker room." Swogger had two touchdown passes to Chambers in the third quarter, the first one set up by a 48-yard run by Brooks-Fletcher. "I knew that once they gave me my chance, I was just going to have to show up," Brooks-Fletcher said. "So I was just waiting for that time and I gues they gave it to me so I tried to amke the most of it." On the second Swogger-to-Chambers touchdown, Chambers caught the ball standing flat-footed in the end zone. "Josh rolled out and the safety and cornerback went with him," Chambers said. "I was standing on the back line and I didn't really do much. Josh threw the ball and that's probably the hardest catch I made all year because I was so open, I didn't want to drop it." Ryan Bagley had five catches for 59 yards while Chambers had four for 43 for the Grizzlies. Derrick Fourroux completed 12-of-20 passes for 116 yards for McNeese State, but fumbled three snaps in the first half. "It was loud, very loud," Fourroux said of the crowd. "As you can tell, I'm a little hoarse." Steven Whitehead caught six passes for 66 yards while Chris Thomas had 10 carries for 56 yards. McNeese State had been averaging 332 yards in total offense, but was held to 224. "I'm sure there's things that we could have done better," Viator said. "But I think Montana's got a real good football team. This is a tough place to play, no question. We knew we were going to have to play as good as we could possibly play today, and we didn't. But they had a lot to do with it, too."
